  # Why: Core creation — full client record with auto-generated fields
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Creating a client record returns the full record with generated fields
    When I create a client with name "Jane Smith", email "jane@example.com", status "active", and jurisdiction "ENG"
    Then the request should succeed with a created status
    And the response should contain a UUID client ID
    And the response should contain a reference matching the pattern "CLT-" followed by 6 digits
    And the response should contain a created_at timestamp
    And the response should contain an updated_at timestamp

  # Why: Core retrieval — get by ID
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Retrieving a client by ID returns the full record
    Given a client "Jane Smith" exists
    When I retrieve the client by their ID
    Then the request should succeed
    And the response should contain the client's full name "Jane Smith"

  # Why: Core update — partial update changes only specified fields
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Updating a client changes only the provided fields
    Given a client "Jane Smith" with status "active" exists
    When I update the client's status to "suspended"
    Then the request should succeed
    And the client's status should be "suspended"
    And the client's full name should still be "Jane Smith"
    And the updated_at timestamp should be later than the created_at timestamp

  # Why: Core list — paginated listing
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Listing clients returns a paginated response
    Given 3 clients exist
    When I list all clients
